Theme of Reading... Hm. To the Audio Book point, broadness is key. If you end up listening to audio books, you haven't read, technically, but you have dramatically increased your exposure to literature. So, make it a Year/Season/Month of Literature instead.



Legal Contracts may award ambiguity to the non-authoring party, but this isn't court, and the importance of victory in a given theme is more important than the needley details. So try to avoid baking any technicalities into them you could get hung up on. If themes work for you, you'll keep using them, so setting them up for as broad a chance of success is key.

snippet.textDisplay: Ngl, i really liked this video. In my college health class, they kept on pressing the SMART goal system for lifestyle changes.  And as someone who has struggled with health their whole life, i knew that setting solid goals with unflexible time lines only leads to disappointment and failure.  They were preaching the use of a system that only really works in relatively short time frames for items that spanned months or years.  Lifestyle Change is slow, and not rigidly defined. Some days you will feel fine, some you may feel great, some not so much.  Some days i felt like i wanted to work out, others i didnt, and that was okay, because overall i was getting better. Chasing perfection every day will only lead to failure, because no one is perfect

snippet.textDisplay: I think another issue with holding to resolutions is that once you get to a new year, you realise that it feels no different to every other year. Without a good point where you feel like 'things are different now' the same lack of motivation follows you. My advice is to just make a change and to make it now. You don't exercise? Do it next weekend. You don't eat healthy? Have a healthy dinner tonight. You don't read enough? Read today. You don't learn new skills? Learn today. Putting off until some arbitrary date sets it up in your mind that that day will feel different, and when it doesn't you lose all motivation. Because janurary 1st feels just like september 13th. But that's all the more reason to start on september 13th. Whatever day it is in the year, make that change now. To wait is to set yourself up for failure.

snippet.textDisplay:
Hashtag, this is the exact opposite of every goal setting strategy I've ever been taught through sports, school, careers or even religion. (Attainable, unchanging outcomes, with an easily definable path, with a specific schedule of deadlines, with rewards/punishments from some source of accountability.)

But I think the issue why most resolutions fail is because the idea behind a resolution usually isn't a specific goal, but for a betterment of yourself. Something a broad theme would better serve. Additionally, failing a "New Year" resolution just gives you an excuse to wait a whole year to next one. A theme doesn't define every day/week as a pass/fail test.

snippet.textDisplay: Sticking with resolutions is easy, but knowing how to fulfil them is nearly impossible. Eat healthy - ok, let's look at that. Oh, nobody knows what we should eat? How is that possible. Read more. Ok, how should I best spend my precious little time? Reading smart novels or something more factual? Because in reality, I should be learning math instead. Learn math. Wow, why is there so much of it, I started practising the basics and after many months I'm still mostly nowhere (in the vastness of it all). Also, I only need the math to excel in the field of computer science, which I should be doing primarily. Also, sports to avoid death, I'm running and it got my knees to be all squeaky. Sticking with resolutions are easy, but coming up with good resolutions and their execution is the hard part where I always fail (by succeeding).

My theme of 2020 could be "Better Business," and I accomplished my first goal of building a proper spreadsheet (my old method on a whiteboard was always makeshift and temporary.... for like 3 years :/ ), before the first month was out! Now it's time for goal #2; finalize the new product design and get it into the store! 2020 is gonna be fun!


I feel like I should explain: I always pick 6 'resolutions' at the beginning of the year, then 6 more in the middle. They are allowed to be the same thing multiple times, if I think the thing will be difficult or time consuming, and I work with a mind toward 'Elon Time,' so if I don't finish one, it can roll over to the next month. The thing/s it displaces just move into the next bracket. I try really hard to make all the goals real, measurable, achievable and important. If a goal is too grandiose, I break it up as sub-goals until it's manageable.

snippet.textDisplay:
I did this actually.
Never had a New Years Resolution before but this year I decided to change something in my life.
Specifically? Mindfulness, relaxation of the mind and acceptance of myself.

I stress myself out a lot, worry a lot, let choices overwhelm and stress me out. I also struggled over the last year or so to accept certain aspects of myself and therefore decided to listen to podcasts related to my life choices, taken up a little bit of meditation, gotten serious about my diet, meeting a therapist once a month, going onto medication for my depression... Just a tonne of stuff that is just looking after me as opposed to worrying about anything else affecting me.

And so far, it's worked and I've never felt more confident, assured and calm in my life.

I typically don't set a resolution, because I know exactly how it'll go. This year, however, I decided to give one a shot: I've had an idea for a novel on the backburner for pretty much all of the 2010s, I finally started writing a draft of it in 2018 but my progress was still too slow for my liking, so late last year I decided to motivate myself: I set a New Year's Resolution for 2020 to have a finished draft of my novel done by midnight on Dec. 31.

It's actually been going fairly well so far; I regrettably still get distracted by social media more than I should, but I have set a lot more time to work on it than I had in the past, and it's starting to bear fruit. Here's hoping I fully keep it!

snippet.textDisplay:
Another thing about resolutions is that when there is a setback, people just give up entirely. "Oh well, there goes another resolution by the wayside. Might as well give up," they say instead of "Hm, okay, that didn't work. Guess I'll try again tomorrow." Some time ago I had a "resolution" about weight loss and nothing much happened for quite a long time, but long about September, I joined a group and started following a plan. Resolution accomplished! A) the resolution itself was not unlike themes as described here and B) I gave myself a break from all the guilt and such that usually accompanies a "broken" resolution and picked it back up at an opportune moment. I figured, if it was the year's resolution, I had all the way until 31 Dec to get started and thus waiting 9 months wasn't a failure. So then, in conjunction with the idea of "season of $thing" if you had a yearly theme of health, you might have a winter of better eating, a spring of taking care of all your annual doctor visits, a summer of exercise, and then if by fall, weight loss isn't already occurring, you could take the foundations you've already built and look at ways that you can ramp them up for even better outcomes.



I like this idea a lot, the Year of (theme). May you get all the shares!

snippet.textDisplay:
TLDR: Think about adding a theme based perspective to your resolutions. IMO ignore the rest of the video because it is a mess.


Lost 20 pounds since December 21st. I don't think specific goals are bad. It's just people often make them unrealistic.


This video is rather confusing because it seems to be a do this not that sort of video. If Grey just advocated for adding a theme based goal as part of a self improvement plan, it would have been fine.


There's also imperfect examples like the tuning fork feels more like a values based perspective. It's not about some hippy resonance concept, it's more finding what kind of values are important to you in order to boost the chances of success.
